|Languages|Philosophy}}\n\n[[Category:Christian genres]]\n[[Category:Cultural anthropology]]\n[[Category:Literature]]\n[[Category:Oral tradition]]\n[[Category:Proverbs| ]]\n[[Category:Literary genres]]\n", "name_user": "Rahul.janagouda", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proverb"}
{"title_page": "Molly Hagan", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Molly Hagan\n|image =\n|imagesize = \n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1961|8|3|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], U.S\n|years_active = 1985&ndash;present\n|occupation = Actress\n|spouse = \n|website = https://mollyhagan.com/}}\n\n'''Molly Joan Hagan''' (born August 3, 1961) is an American actress. She co-starred in films ''[[Code of Silence (1985 film)|Code of Silence]]'' (1985), ''[[Some Kind of Wonderful (film)|Some Kind of Wonderful]]'' (1987), ''[[The Dentist]]'' (1996), ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' (1999) and ''[[Sully (film)|Sully]]'' (2016), and is also known for her roles in television on ''[[Herman's Head]]'' (1991\u20131994) and ''[[Unfabulous]]'' (2004\u20132007).\n\n==Life and career==\nHagan was born in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]],<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/29538/Molly-Hagen/biography | title=Molly Hagen Biography | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> the daughter of Mary Elizabeth ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Henslee) and John Robert Hagan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/22/Molly-Hagan.html|title=Molly Hagan Biography (1961-)|website=www.filmreference.com}}</ref> She was raised in [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] and attended [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nHagan played Diana Luna alongside [[Chuck Norris]] on the 1985 action film ''[[Code of Silence (1985 film)|Code of Silence]]''. Hagan has made appearances in films such as ''[[Some Kind of Wonderful (film)|Some Kind of Wonderful]]'' and most notably as the young [[Miss Ellie Ewing]] in the television movie ''[[Dallas: The Early Years]]''<ref name=\"bio\"/> (a prequel of the long-running soap opera ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'') and she has appeared in several other television series, including the 1980s situation comedy ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' as Caroline, the daughter of Miles Webber, Rose's romantic partner.\n\nHagan starred in the cult series ''[[Nutt House]]'', which had a six-week run in 1989, and ''[[Herman's Head]]'' which ran on Fox from 1991 to 1994. She portrayed Angel, one of the four characters inside Herman, and represented his sensitivity. She was in two episodes of the detective mystery series ''[[Columbo]]'', namely ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 8|Murder, Smoke and Shadows]]'' (1989), and ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 10 and specials|Butterfly in Shades of Grey]]'' (1994). She also appeared twice on ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'' (in two different roles). In the end of the second season of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', she played a young Vorta called Eris in \"[[The Jem'Hadar]]\". She appeared in three episodes of the third season of ''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]'', she also appeared on ''[[Seinfeld]]'' as Sister Roberta, the Latvian Orthodox novice that Kramer nearly took from the church, and a cooking teacher on ''[[Friends]]''. She played a trailer trash mother in a Jerry Springer-based movie, ''Ringmaster''. She played Diane McAllister in the 1999 movie ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' opposite [[Matthew Broderick]]. Hagan also played Coach Crenshaw in ''[[Air Bud: Seventh Inning Fetch]]''.\n\nHagan played the mother of [[Emma Roberts]]'s character Addie in the [[Nickelodeon]] series ''[[Unfabulous]]'' from 2004 to 2007. She also made a guest appearances in many television series, such as ''[[Charmed]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'', ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'', ''[[Cold Case]]'', ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'', ''[[The Closer]]'', and ''[[NYPD Blue]]''. Hagan also appeared in [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Princess Protection Program]]'' in 2009, and had another guest appearance in an episode of the Disney Channel sitcom ''[[Liv and Maddie]]''. In 2014, Hagan was cast as the lead character's mother in [[The CW]] series, ''[[IZombie (TV series)|IZombie]]'', based on the DC Comics.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/08/20/izombie-molly-hagan-judy-reyes/ | title='iZombie' recasts mom, adds 'Devious Maids' star | publisher=Entertainment Weekly | date=August 20, 2014 | accessdate=21 August 2014 | author=Natalie Abrams}}</ref> She later made recurring guest appearances in ''[[Jane the Virgin]]'' and ''[[The Orville]]'', ''[[No Good Nick]]'' and ''[[Truth Be Told (2019 TV series)|Truth Be Told]]''. In 2017 she co-starred in the NBC limited series ''[[Law & Order True Crime]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/law-order-true-crime-the-menendez-murders-sterling-beaumon-molly-hagan-dominic-flores-cast-1202114499/|title=\u2018Law & Order True Crime: The Menendez Murders\u2019: Sterling Beaumon, Molly Hagan & Dominic Flores Join Cast|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> and in 2020 was cast in a series regular role as title character mother in the CW crime series, ''[[Walker, Texas Ranger]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/molly-hagan-the-cw-walker-texas-ranger-reboot-1202869991/|title=Molly Hagan To Co-Star In The CW\u2019s \u2018Walker, Texas Ranger\u2019 Reboot|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Code of Silence (1985 film)|Code of Silence]]''\n| Diana Luna\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Some Kind of Wonderful (film)|Some Kind of Wonderful]]''\n| Shayne\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Fresh Horses (film)|Fresh Horses]]''\n| Ellen\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[French Exit (1995 film)|French Exit]]''\n| Alice\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[The Dentist]]''\n| Jessica\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Sometimes They Come Back... Again]]''\n| Officer Violet Searcey\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Ringmaster (film)|Ringmaster]]''\n| Connie Zorzak\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]''\n| Diane McAllister\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Playing Mona Lisa]]''\n| Jenine Goldstein\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Miracle in Lane 2]]''\n| Sheila Yoder\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Air Bud: Seventh Inning Fetch]]''\n| Coach Crenshaw\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Defining Maggie]]''\n| Maggie\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''They Shoot Divas, Don't They?''\n| Diane\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Tom's Nu Heaven''\n| Dr. Randy\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Holly Hobbie and Friends: Best Friends Forever''\n| Teresa \n| Voice role\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Henry Poole Is Here]]''\n| Pediatrician\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''The Babysitter ''\n| Mrs. Jones\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Lucky Ones (film)|The Lucky Ones]] ''\n| Pat Cheaver\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Just Peck]] ''\n| Ms. Sears\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Cost of Living''\n| Penny\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Love Shack (film)|Love Shack]]''\n| Debbie Vanderspiegl\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Red State (2011 film)|Red State]] ''\n| Janet Keenan\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Miss Dial]] ''\n| Potato Shredder Caller\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[BFFs]]''\n| Rebecca\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Ask Me Anything (film)|Ask Me Anything]]''\n| Caroline Kampenfelt\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Not Safe for Work (film)|Not Safe for Work]]''\n| Janine\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Last Light]]''\n| Meryl\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Cheater, Cheater''\n| Candace\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Navy Seals vs. Zombies]]''\n|CIA Agent Stacy Thomas\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Step 9''\n|Janine\n|Short film \n|-\n|2015\n|''[[We Are Your Friends (film)|We Are Your Friends]]''\n|Francine\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Sully (film)|Sully]]''\n|Doreen Welsh\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[The Keeping Hours]]''\n|Daniels\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''The Garage Sale ''\n|Sophie\n|Also writer and producer \n|-\n|2019\n|''ism''\n|Sophie\n|-\n|2019\n|''Boris and the Bomb''\n|Dani\n| \n|-\n|2019\n|''When We Dance''\n|Emilia\n|Short film\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! 